# OOPS Concepts in Java – Clear and Detailed Explanation

## What is OOPS?

**OOPS (Object-Oriented Programming System)** is a programming approach that organizes software around **objects and classes** rather than functions and logic.

Java uses OOPS concepts to make programs:

* Reusable
* Secure
* Easy to maintain
* Easy to understand

### Definition

**Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)** is a programming paradigm that uses objects and classes to design and develop applications based on real-world entities.

---

# Basic Terminologies in OOPS

## 1. Class

### Definition

A **class** is a blueprint or template used to create objects.

It contains:

* Data (Variables)
* Methods (Functions)

### Example

```java
class Student
{
    int id;
    String name;

    void display()
    {
        System.out.println(id + " " + name);
    }
}
```

Here, `Student` is a class.

---

## 2. Object

### Definition

An **object** is an instance of a class.

When memory is allocated to a class, an object is created.

### Example

```java
public class Main
{
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        Student s1 = new Student();

        s1.id = 101;
        s1.name = "Suresh";

        s1.display();
    }
}
```

### Output

```text
101 Suresh
```

---

# Four Pillars of OOPS

1. Encapsulation
2. Inheritance
3. Polymorphism
4. Abstraction

---

# 1. Encapsulation

## Definition

**Encapsulation** is the process of wrapping data (variables) and methods (functions) into a single unit and restricting direct access to data.

It is achieved using:

* Private variables
* Public getter and setter methods

### Real-Life Example

A capsule contains medicine inside a protective cover.

Similarly, data is protected inside a class.

### Example

```java
class Employee
{
    private int salary;

    public void setSalary(int salary)
    {
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    public int getSalary()
    {
        return salary;
    }
}

public class Main
{
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        Employee e = new Employee();

        e.setSalary(50000);

        System.out.println(e.getSalary());
    }
}
```

### Output

```text
50000
```

### Advantages of Encapsulation

* Data security
* Data hiding
* Better control over data
* Easy maintenance

---

# 2. Inheritance

## Definition

**Inheritance** is the process by which one class acquires the properties and methods of another class.

The existing class is called:

* Parent Class
* Super Class
* Base Class

The new class is called:

* Child Class
* Derived Class
* Sub Class

### Syntax

```java
class Parent
{
}

class Child extends Parent
{
}
```

### Example

```java
class Animal
{
    void eat()
    {
        System.out.println("Animal Eats");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal
{
    void bark()
    {
        System.out.println("Dog Barks");
    }
}

public class Main
{
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        Dog d = new Dog();

        d.eat();
        d.bark();
    }
}
```

### Output

```text
Animal Eats
Dog Barks
```

### Advantages

* Code reusability
* Reduces duplication
* Easy extension of programs

---

## Types of Inheritance

### 1. Single Inheritance

```text
A → B
```

One child inherits from one parent.

---

### 2. Multilevel Inheritance

```text
A → B → C
```

A chain of inheritance.

---

### 3. Hierarchical Inheritance

```text
      A
     / \
    B   C
```

Multiple child classes inherit from one parent.

---

### 4. Multiple Inheritance

```text
A + B → C
```

Not supported using classes in Java.

Supported using Interfaces.

---

# 3. Polymorphism

## Definition

**Polymorphism** means "One Name, Many Forms."

A single method can perform different tasks depending on the situation.

### Types

1. Compile-Time Polymorphism
2. Run-Time Polymorphism

---

## A. Method Overloading (Compile-Time Polymorphism)

### Definition

Multiple methods having:

* Same name
* Different parameters

### Example

```java
class Addition
{
    int add(int a, int b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }

    int add(int a, int b, int c)
    {
        return a + b + c;
    }
}
```

### Output

```text
add(10,20)      = 30
add(10,20,30)   = 60
```

---

## B. Method Overriding (Run-Time Polymorphism)

### Definition

A child class provides its own implementation of a method already defined in the parent class.

### Example

```java
class Animal
{
    void sound()
    {
        System.out.println("Animal Sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal
{
    void sound()
    {
        System.out.println("Dog Barks");
    }
}

public class Main
{
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        Animal a = new Dog();

        a.sound();
    }
}
```

### Output

```text
Dog Barks
```

### Advantages

* Flexibility
* Dynamic method execution
* Better scalability

---

# 4. Abstraction

## Definition

**Abstraction** means hiding implementation details and showing only the essential features to the user.

### Real-Life Example

When driving a car:

* You use steering, brakes, accelerator.
* You don't need to know the internal engine mechanism.

This is abstraction.

---

## Achieving Abstraction

1. Abstract Class
2. Interface

---

## Abstract Class

### Definition

A class declared with the `abstract` keyword.

It may contain:

* Abstract methods
* Normal methods

### Example

```java
abstract class Vehicle
{
    abstract void start();
}

class Car extends Vehicle
{
    void start()
    {
        System.out.println("Car Starts");
    }
}
```

---

## Interface

### Definition

An interface contains abstract methods that must be implemented by a class.

### Example

```java
interface Shape
{
    void draw();
}

class Circle implements Shape
{
    public void draw()
    {
        System.out.println("Drawing Circle");
    }
}
```

---

# Constructor

## Definition

A constructor is a special method used to initialize objects.

### Characteristics

* Same name as class name
* No return type
* Automatically called when object is created

### Example

```java
class Student
{
    Student()
    {
        System.out.println("Constructor Called");
    }
}
```

---

# this Keyword

## Definition

The `this` keyword refers to the current object of the class.

### Example

```java
class Student
{
    int id;

    Student(int id)
    {
        this.id = id;
    }
}
```

---

# super Keyword

## Definition

The `super` keyword refers to the parent class object.

### Example

```java
class Animal
{
    String color = "White";
}

class Dog extends Animal
{
    String color = "Black";

    void display()
    {
        System.out.println(super.color);
    }
}
```

### Output

```text
White
```

